I"&<p>An <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/virtual-reality-renders-abstract-concepts-into-tangible-objects">object</a> or <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/manifolds-formalize-emergence">manifold</a> is aligned with itself, by <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/dictionary-definitions-enable-one-shot-concept-learning">definition</a>. If one of them is aligned to another, then the other is also aligned to them. Additionally, if two of them are aligned to a third, then both are aligned. In this, alignment is <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/modal-logic-proper-enables-possible-worlds-semantics">reflexive, symmetric, and transitive</a>, as can be seen in <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/similar-embodiment-predicts-manifold-alignment">embodiment</a>, <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/similar-cultural-embedding-predicts-manifold-alignment">culture</a>, and <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/explicit-language-of-mental-states-informs-psycholinguistic-manifold-alignment">language</a>.</p>
